Patch Set 17:

(3 comments)

Some small details inline. Also, I have a more generic question (which could be seen as a follow-up). I see we have several tasks where we use the following construction:

- name: task X - opendistro
  ...
  when: elasticsearch_distro | lower == 'opendistro'
- name: Task X - opensearch
  ...
  when: elasticsearch_distro | lower == 'opensearch'

Maybe we could improve readability of the setup if we had all those tasks in separate playbooks, and extracted the opendistro/opensearch selection logic  elsewhere? Something like having two blocks in tasks/main.yaml, one if we're running opendistro and a different one if running opensearch.

FYI, I don't want to maintain two deployments, where one is EOL (opendistro), so in the future

I don't want to do that in one patch set, but maybe it will be better to review.

> What the point to keep opendistro support in the role ?
> Do we have deployment in our infra that use the current role ?

We will not use that role in sf-config, just in sf-infra. 
The opendistro is already running on the production and the TripleO team can communicate with it. The opensearch has same configuration as opendistro, but it is a new software and I hope there will be no situation, that we will find a bug that will block the other teams of using opensearch. In the future, I plan to drop support for opendistro moreover it can be done now it this ps or in next.
We only have CI job (sf-ci-functional-external-elk) that is validating the current role. Patch set for deploying opensearch host is here: https://softwarefactory-project.io/r/c/software-factory/sf-infra/+/22611 but it waits for merge all changes for that project.

Patch Set 3:

Wouldn't it be more clean trying to keep SNO in line with how IPI installer already works? What I mean is: add the right lines to ~/.bashrc so the oc calls work transparently. I think something like this can work:
```
if [ -f ~/.dci-sno ]; then
  export KUBECONFIG=/path/to/kc
fi;
```

Then touch/remove that file appropriately if you're using SNO.

What do you think?

Patch Set 3:

I'm actually adding the KUBECONFIG var in the .bashrc file, please see https://softwarefactory-project.io/r/c/dci-openshift-agent/+/22518/7/roles/sno-installer/tasks/60_deploy_sno.yml#2
However, as I mentioned in the commit the moment I use ansible_connection=local in the ansible inventory, any variables I set in ~/.bashrc are not loaded/used by ansible, I tested in RHEL 8.4 and Fedora 34. Here an example: https://gist.github.com/manurodriguez/dde955f37954af93909320c37ce991c8

Why am I using ansible_connection=local? because if not the DCI_* variables of the remoteci are not loaded after being exported in the bash session and jobs fail to create. 

Having said all this, if don't use ansible_connection=local and I import both the dcirc variables and KUBECONFIG in .bashrc all works without having to modify this task or the one in PR 22553, so I think I'm going to stick to that, I wanted to have both options to be more flexible, but it's just adding more complexity.

Patch Set 3:

I'm abandoning this change, I'm injecting DCI variables on .bashrc and not using ansible_connection=local anymore to keep it simple.

Patch Set 15:

I have one more comment (maybe other people can correct me if I am wrong). You can also think on defining the new variables you are creating (max_image_age and cleanup_old_images) in a specific file. I think there are two ways:
- Using the dci-openshift-agent/group_vars/all file (but maybe it is a generic file).
- Moving your new code to a role, under dci-openshift-agent/roles/<your_role>/tasks/main.yml, and define the new variables in dci-openshift-agent/roles/<your_role>/defaults/main.yml. You can check the roles directory to see examples about how to do this.
